The Art of Data Visualization¶

Data Visualization is the practice (and art) of creating a visual representation of information that conveys insight , tells a story or summarizes data.

boston = pd.read_csv('2017BostonMarathonTop1000.csv')

We use Bar charts when we need to plot Numerical value across different levels of a Categorical value for example : "Number of Ivy League Students by State" , "Number of Marathon runners by Age"

Marathon runners by Age(Category)¶

'Age' is going to be our categorical value. We are going to count the number of runners within that Age and that is going to be our Numerical value.

  • Lets start by isolating our Categorical variable.

How to produce Horizontal Bar charts¶

  • Horizontal Bar charts are similar to Regular bar charts but flipped 180 degrees
In [84]:
#kind = barh

In [86]:
#Sorted in Descending order
ax = boston.Age.value_counts(ascending = True).plot(kind = 'barh' , figsize = (10 , 5));

ax.set_ylabel('Number of Runners');
  • But in our use case with so many categories, its getting a bit difficult to process all of these output
  • It would be better with fewer categories

- Wine consumption by continent
- XBOX sales by country
- Marathon runners by Gender

PIE PLOTS¶

When to use PIE charts:¶

  • Just like BAR charts , PIE charts also show a numerical amount against different levels of a Categorical value. With PIE charts , the focus is on attributing a TOTAL amount into its components.
  • Whereas with BAR charts the focus is usually only to show absolute amounts in each category side by side rectangular BAR layout.
In [92]:
games = pd.read_csv('games_sales.csv')

HISTOGRAMS¶

https://www.udemy.com/course/the-ultimate-pandas-bootcamp-advanced-python-data-analysis/learn/lecture/19512848#overview

In [12]:
drinks = pd.read_csv('drinks.csv')

Histograms are charts that plot the distribution of a Numeric value as a Series of bars.

  • Each of the bars cover a fixed range of values that is called the Bin-Size.
  • And the height of the bar indicate the frequency of values that falls in that bin size
  • We use Histograms when we are interested in understanding how a given numerical field is distributed
  • With Histograms we are trying to answer questions like , In what range do the most common values fall
  • Or is the distribution Left or Right Skewed
  • Are there one or two modes or peaks

drinks.head(2)

  • We know this because , we can see that the tallest bar is between 0 to 50 range

ax = drinks.beer_servings.plot(kind= 'hist');

How wide should the Bins be?¶

Its really something that we should determine when we Analyse the data and understand it better

In [21]:
#The default bin size is 10 in Matplotlib
#Bin size or Number of Bins
In [18]:
#With bin size = 5 , we have lost some level of detail
ax = drinks.beer_servings.plot(kind= 'hist' , bins = 5);
ax.set_xlabel('Beer Servings');
  • As we increase the number of Beer Servings , the number of countries in each bin monotonously decreases
In [19]:
ax = drinks.beer_servings.plot(kind= 'hist' , bins = 15);
ax.set_xlabel('Beer Servings');
  • Now if we change the bin size , it still implies that as we increase the number of Beer Servings , the number of countries decreases, but its not as monotonous as we first thought.
In [20]:
ax = drinks.beer_servings.plot(kind= 'hist' , bins = 35);
ax.set_xlabel('Beer Servings');
  • The distribution starts to get very rough
  • Perhaps there is a lot of noise here to freally infer much insight
  • Its upto us to understand our data better and plot the required bin size

Note : Not too much noise and enough detail are important aspects to be taken care of

  • Te distributions overlapped significantly and are overshadowing one another
In [28]:
#We change the Opacity
drinks.loc[: , 'beer_servings' : 'wine_servings'].plot(kind = 'hist' , alpha = 0.6);
  • It still feels like an overloaded histogram
In [31]:
drinks.loc[: , 'beer_servings' : 'wine_servings'].plot(kind = 'hist' , subplots = True , figsize = (7,7));

Just like Histograms , Scatterplots are also used with Numeric values. But instead of helping us understand the Distribution of a Single variable, Scatterplots help highlight the relationship between two variables.

How good is the relationship between different Sections in the SAT section.¶

(Math , Reading , Writing)

Hypothesis : Reading and Writing are more strongly associated than writing and Math ?¶

Is this hypothesis supported by our Dataset?

  • There seems to be a Strong Positive Correlation
  • There is also lesser variability around the correlation line compared to what we saw with "Math" above
  • There are fewer outliers
In [51]:
reading.corr(writing)
Out[51]:
0.9854389581058107
  • Almost 0.99 Correlation which is veryclose to perfect Positive Correlation which is indicated by 1

Conclusion :¶

  • The Average SAT section scores across New York City High schools are on average Strongly positively associated, with "Reading" and "Writing" much more positively correlated compared to "Writing" and "Math"
